Raedwulf:<br>
<br>
I take offense at the use of the term redneck in the way it was used as well.  While I read your explanation about your intent when using it, it still came across as offensive to me.  Are only white people who get sunburned necks racist?  No.  Are white people who get sunburned necks found only in the South?  No.  Yet your statements and the words used suggest that by their everyday common usage.  Just because I live in Georgia and not New York City (thank God, I personally would hate it there), I am not an uneducated, backward ass redneck (and by implication a racist).<br>
<br>
As Ceru said, it is upsetting that the South is perceived as a hotbed of racism and *primitive/ignorant/insert derogatory term here* thinking.  Yes, the South has racism, yes everywhere in the world has racism.  I do find it funny that despite Southern racism supposedly being so overt and oppresive, every major race riot since the 60's when overt racism practices were ended, where people were injured by each other (not riot police), has occurred in big cities like L.A., Detroit, etc.  Food for thought.<br>
<br>
<br>
About reparations:<br>
<br>
The truly sad thing about the reparations discussion is who is being victimized in its name.  There have been a few brave reports on the fraud that is being perpetuated on black people by other black people using this issue.  I say brave because it seems the media is often too paralyzed from fears of being perceived as racist to even report on the activities of racial interest groups.<br>
<br>
While there are some legitimate attempts to seek reparations, all too often donations are gathered by black racists asking for money to fight the white devil and &quot;get people paid.&quot;<br>
<br>
When these same people are questioned about the money and what activities they have participated in to further the reparations movement, the answer is &quot;no comment&quot;, and the tax records show  .... you guessed it: $0 contributions.  <br>
<br>
In other words, it is just like donating money to supposedly feed starving children (or some other noble sounding charity) and finding out the solicitor just pocketed your money.  Obviously I am diametrically opposed to the idea of slavery reparations, but I dislike people using any agenda people believe in to personally profit from it.<br>
<br>
And the victims of this fraud are most often unsophisticated, poor black people who are told they *will* get money for this.  That the money is already allocated, etc.  These people deserve the most protection from these racial predators and their disgusting practices, and yet authorities and media seem paralyzed with how to deal with it.  I have no solution, but I find it sad. <p>Impresario Wyvern Wyrmsong <br>
