I understand the connotations and denotations of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> redneck</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
The irony of it is that the word is a bigot's term.<br>
<br>
It is a derogatory term used to alienate and delineate a group of people for perceived and assumed differences that are based purely on stereotypical generalizations.<br>
<br>
Are bigoted black people rednecks?  No. They're bigoted black people.<br>
.................chinese people? No. No. They're bigoted Chinese people.<br>
<br>
Only bigoted white people are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> rednecks</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Rednecks, in both denotation and connotation, are white people of lower socio-economic standing with sub par educations that are generally known to have vocal opinions about race divisions and local community pride.<br>
<br>
Now here is the kicker.<br>
<br>
Can we give bigoted black people a derogatory term? <br>
No, because that would be racist.<br>
<br>
To end racism you must well.. uh.. stop being racist.  <br>
That goes for all sides.<br>
<br>
Double standards are alive and well.<br>
<br>
Ceru<br>
